{"/service/ndnp/nmu/batch_nmu_graywolf_ver02/data/sn86063823/0029602580A/1908011501/0048.xml":{"full_text":"10SWIELL Mf LI WHMtik\nVOLUME 5.\nROSWELL, NEW MEXICO, WEDNESDAY EVENING, JANUARY IS, 1908\nNUMBER 270\nV\nJ\nf\nONE HUNDRED AND SIXTY\nTWO BODIES RECOVERED.\nBoyertown, Pa., Jan. 15. The four\nImprovised morgues contained this\nmorning the bodies of 102 victims of\nthe opera house fire. Undertakers\nfrom neighboring cities were pressed\nInto service to care for bodies as they\nwere brought from the ruins. To each\nbody and the articles found on it\nwere attached numbers for identifica\ntion. Few bodies can be identified by\nthe features. When the morgues were\nopened today hundreds of people\nwere waiting in expectancy of find\ning the ,todies of loved ones.\nCoroner Strassen said the scene\nat the opera house was the saddest\npicture he ever looked upon, simply\nIndescribable. \"I shall make a thor\nough investigation,\" he said.\nHenry Fisher, the operator of the\ncalcium light, escaped with severe\nburns. \"The accident,\" he said, \"was\ncaused 'by the cap on one of the tanks\nblowing out, and this scaTed the peo\nple. I finally got the leak repaired,\nand just as I had the people calmed,\nthe foolish action of some thoroughly\nfrightened persons on the stage caus\ned the upsetting of an oil lamp and\nconsequent spread of Sanies which\nnothing could avert.\"\nThat the victims were not confined\nto residents of Boyertown is shown\nby the number of unclaimed teams\nat the hotels and staibles. Fully forty\nteams remained unclaimed yesterday.\nThey are said to belong to people re\nsiding within a radius of five or six\nmiles of Boyertown, who drove to\nthis place Monday to witness the\nproduction of the \"Scottish Reforma\ntion.\" There is no clue to the owner\nship of a number of the teams.\nNOTICE.\nTo the stockholders and mem\nbers of the Southwestern\nSavings,, Loan and Building\nAssociation of Las Vegas,\nN. M.\nYou are hereby notified\nthat Mr. R. H. McCune, of Ros\nwell, N. M., \"having resigned\nhis position as our agent in\nthe Pecos Valley,\" has been\nre-appointed by this Associa\ntion to take charge of our af\nfairs in all the towns in the\nPecos Valley, Ibeginning with\nPortales on the north and\nsouth to Carlsbad, N. M.\n(Signed) Southwestern Sav\nings, Loan a\"d Building As\nsociation, By C. E. PERRY,\nSecretary.\nI have arranged with Mr.\nAlbert Hanny, assistant cashier\nof First National Bank, of\nRoswell, N. M., to act as col\nlector for the above named\nAssociation. Therefore, all\nmembers in Roswell are here\nby notified to make future\npayments to Mr. Hanny, who\nw ill receipt for same.\nR. H. McCUNE.\nMusical Comedy at Majestic. t\nCommencing Thursday, Jan. 16tn,\nfor three nights. The Allen Curtis\nMusical Comedy Company, who are\nmaking such a good reputation in this\nsection of the country, will be here\nwithus next Thursday, Jan. 16th for\nthree nights in the funniest of all\nmusical plays, \"Jakey, Mikey and\nIkey,\" \"A New York Girl,\" and \"A\nJolly Widow.\" The company numbers\n25 -people headed with that clever\ncharacter comedian Allen Curtis, and\nhe Is surrounded with such a well\nknown cast of musical comedy play\ners, that the scarcely need an intro\nduction to its patrons.\nCotton seed cake and meal at the\nRoswell Wool Hide Co., phone 30.\nSHEEP MEN SEND WHITE\nADVICE BY TELEGRAPH.\nSince the news of Elza White's\nrobbery at Amarillo was published,\nhis friends among the sheep men\nhave worried considerably about it,\n-and arc afraid, he will adopt the\nwrong trail somewhere on his long\ntrip to and from Helena, Mont. Some\nof them think that perhaps it was a\n-\"put up job,\" and that A. D. Garrett\nSiad a hand in the \"robbery.\" To be\non the safe side- the following tele\ngram was sent this morning to .him\nat Helena: \"Don't tell the convention\nthat- the cow men rohbed your at\nAmarillo, Elza. We don't believe it.\"\n(Signed) \"Chaves County Sheep\nBreeders' and Wool Growers' Asso\nciation.\" The message was sent \"col\nlect.\" Banquet Tickets Only $1.50\nIt was reported yesterday that the\ntickets to the Boosters' Banquet were\ntoeing sold at $2. The price of the\ntickets is 1.50\nELKS MAY ESTABLISH\nA NATIONAL HOME.\nSanta Fe New Mexican Special.\nRaton, N. M., Jan. 11. Considera\nble interest has been juanifested by\nmembers of the B. P. O. Elks of Col\nfax county in the proposal to pur\nchase the Abreu Rayado ranch locat\ned in the southern portion of this\ncounty for an Elks' resort and home.\nThe plan advanced is to make the\nproposition a territorial affair and\nnerhaps enlist the members of the\norder iroughout the United States\nThe ranch is an extensive property,\nand abounds with wild game. It\nwould also be possible to enclose the\ngrounds and import em from w yom\nlng or Montana to make the game re-\nomhlomAtio of the order.\nThe ranch has fine mountain\nstreams traversing it which already\nabound with trout. The scenery is\nsurpassed by ao other region in the\nUnited States and the resort could\n;be reached by a short stage drive\nfrom a trunk line of railway, the\nAtchison, Topeka .Santa Fe.\nThe suggestion is made that the\nmoney could be raised, if it was de\ncided to make the institution a nation\nal home and resort, by asking the\npayment of ten or fifteen cents from\neach member of the order to be col\nlected through the local lodges. A\nsanatorium could be maintained for\nsick members, as the climate is ex\ntraordinarily good, which would fill a\nlong felt need of the order through\nout the country.\nShould, that method not be found\nfeasible, the grounds could be pur\nchased by making the resort a stock\nconcern and selling shares at $100\na share which would entitle the hold\ner to all the privileges of the grounds\nexcept the expense of iboard while\nspending a vacation at the resort.\nThe local officers of lodges \"irough-\nout the territory are to be urged to\ntake up the consideration of the mat\nter in their meetings, so that the\nvote can be taken on the proposition\nand plans put into effect for carry\ning out the suggestion.\nThe Artesia Nursery.\nFor Fruit, Shade and Ornamental\ntrees, see J. S. Highsmith, Artesia,\nor Wyatt Johnson, Roswell. 61tf\no\nLLOYD GENTER COMPANY\nDRAWS ANOTHER BIG CROWD\nFully as many people were out to\nthe Majestic theatre last night as on\nthe opening night of the Lloyd and\nCenter Company, both audiences be\ning large. On last night the company\nplayed \"Black Diamond,\" and many\ndeclared it to be better than the op\nening bill, which proved to be quite\npopular. The specialties last night\nwere good, including songs and dances\nand instrumental music. The com\npany concludes its engagement to\nnight with \"The Girl from Cuba.\"\nRussell does horse-shoeing.\nlOtf\nFive cents per pound is what you\nhave to pay for fine apples at the\nCash Grocery. tf\nDANGER IN MOVING\nPICTURE MACHINES.\nNew York, Jan. 15. While it is\nnow said that the terrible tragedy at\nBoyertown. Pa., in which nearly two\nhundred lives were lost, was not di\nrectly caused hy the moving picture\nmachine as first reported, the report\nhas called attention to the danger of\nthese machines, many of which are\nin daily and nightly operation in New\nYork and other cities. Fire Chief Cro\nker says there is great danger of fire\nfrom these. Very often the fire depart\nment is called out on account of a\nblaze originating thus. The danger is\ngreatest in small show operated m\nstores unprovided with sufficient ex\nits. o\nRussell builds new wagons. lOtf\nFOR CITY CLERK.\nA direct move in the city election\ncampaign was made today by W. H.\nCosgrove, who announces himself a\ncandidate for City Clerk. Mr. Cos-\nErrove is a Missourian, and came here\nfirst in 1879. He was receiver of the\nlocal land office for four years, and\nbeginning with Cleveland's first term\nwas in the postoffice nine years alto\ngether, holding over under Harrison,\nbeing retained during Cleveland's sec\nond term, and working for awhile as\nclerk while the late W. D. Mathews\nwas postmaster. Mr. Cosgrove has al\nso 'been engaged in the mercantile\nbusiness here, and is well known to\neverybody as a man well qualified to\nfill the office of city clerk. For nearly\n25 years he has been a resident and\nproperty owner of Roswell. At pres\nent he is not actively engaged in bus-\nness. A little over a year ago he re\nturned to Roswell from. Silver City,\nwhere he had gone with the inten\ntion of making his permanent home.\nAfter retiring from business, however.\nold associations drew aim back to\nRoswell.\nMoney to Loan. Roswell\nTitle and\nTrust Co.\nThe Watson-Finley Grocery Co. has\npurchased the entire stock of grocer\nies of the Cash Grocery Co. and op\nened the same for business at the\nsame location as before. We respect\nfully solicit a portion of your patron\nage. This store will be strictly cash,\nand we intend to give the people full\nvalue for their money. Watson-Finley\nGrocery Co. 68t3\nJ. B. Trotter Gets Fine Well.\nA big well has been brought in for\nJ. B. Trotter on his place a half mile\neast of the round-house of the rail\nroad, on lot 13. Belle Plaine. The well\nis 720 feet deep, has a casing of 6 5-8\ninches and the water flows 41 inches\na;bove the top, indicating an approx\nimate flow of 1,500 gallons per min\nute. Russell does boiler work.\nlOtf\nJ. J. Cole, of Big Springs, Texas,\nwrites that he will return to Roswell\nwithin a few days to re-open the Ros\nwell Machine Shops, which are located\non South Main street. He also states\nthat he is bringing a good crew of\nfirst class workmen and will be able\nto do tie fcest of everything in black\nsniithing,\n263tX\nONE STORE UNTOUCHED\nBY FINANCIAL PANIC.\nThe Record would call your atten\ntion to the bold and prosperous look\ning ad. of the Sorosis shoe on anoth\ner page, signed by Price Co., as a\nI testimonial that prosperity continues\nin Roswell despite the financial panic\nI elsewhere. One of the strict rules of\ni the Sorosis Company is that they ex\npect their agents to fit all their shoes\nin the store. They are not allowed\nto send out any \"on suspicion\" or\napproval. They wish to know that tihe\ncustomer is entirely satisfied before\nleaving the store, so that there shall\nnot be the slightest misunderstanding\nas to the guaranty made.\nBy taking the utmost pains to\nplease every customer, the firm of\nPrice Co. is one of the few firms\nin the country that keeps Its full\nforce employed and business increas\ning even through the dull season. It\nis all in the method of handling the\ntrade and having the goods just as\nrepresented in every particularly. For\nmerly Price Co. did quite a large\ncredit .business, which they have cut\ndown to a minimum.; but their cash\ntrade more than doubled in the past\nyear, owing to careful attention to\nevery detail of catering to the most\nluxurious taste, as well as courteous\nand accommodating service to the\nmost economical buyer of staples\nand absolute necessaries. The person\nwho buys a dollars worth of goods at\nthis store is treated just as well as\nthe person who buys hundreds of\ndollars. In building for the future no\nbody knows how soon the small pur\nchaser may become the largest of\nall. Price Co. are always in the\nmarket with the very latest and new\nest fabrics and novelties.\nGrill Cafe for Sale.\nCall at the Roswell Hardware Co.\nfor particulars. 59tf\nJOHN DAVISSON TO BE\nBURIED AT HAGERMAN\nA telephone message to the Record\nfrom Editor J. D. Mell, of Hagerman,\nbrought the news today that word\nhad been received from Brownwood,\nTexas, giving meager details of the\nkilling of John Davisson, son of W.\nS. Davisson of Hagerman, at Brown\nwood Monday.- He -was working near\nthe home of his uncle with a stump-\npuller when the lever on the machine\nbroke and struck him in a vital spot.\nThe -boy's father will arrive in Hag\nerman Friday morning with the 'body,\nnd the funeral will occur at that\nplace Fri.lay at ten o'clock. Burial\nwill be made at Hagerman.\no\nApples,' apples, yes lots of them,\nat the Cash Grocery at only 5c per\npound. tf\nYOUNG LADIES ORGANIZE\nQUEEN ESTHER CIRCLE.\nThe young ladies of the First M.\nE. church, and their friends, met at\nthe .home of Dr. Armstrong, 604 N.\nMo. ave., Tuesday evening, and org\nanized a Queen Esther Circle with\n15 charter members. The following\nofficers were elected: President, Mrs.\nWilfred Smith; Vice President, Miss\nElida King; Secretary, Mrs. W. J.\nArmstrong; Corresponding Secretary,\nMiss Mary Mohler; Treasurer, Miss\nFern Fairchild. After the organization\na social time ensued ana reiresu-\nments were served.\no\nSHADE TREES.\nAll kinds first class planted and\nguaranteed to grow. We also carry a\nfull line of fruit trees. Office 2nd and\nMain St. in Seed Store.\nTHE SPENCER SEEDLESS\nAPPLE CO.\nREAL ESTATE MEN.\nALL real estate men or parties in\nterested in the sale of real estate in\nor near Roswell are requested to be\npresent and meet with the Roswell\nRealty Board in the office of the Ros\nwell Title Trust Co. on next Friday\nevening at 7:30 for the purpose of\ndiscussing the advisability of main\ntaining an advertising office at Ama\nrillo, Texas. 3t\nR. H. M'CUNE, Secy.\nThe Cash Grocerv is the nlace to\nget your apples at only 5c per pound.\nRHUBARB ROOTS for sale, 60c\nper doz. 210 S. Ky. ave. 68t3\nA SUGGESTION CONCERNING\nCHARITY ORGANIZATION\nEditor Daily Record: \"A Commu\nnication\" signed John W. Smith sug\ngests that a charity organization so\nciety be inaugurated in Roswell.\nA society for caring for the poor\nis absolutely necessary in this city.\nBut why create a charity organiza\ntion? Surely the Salvation Army ias\ndone a most useful work for the re\nlief and abolition of poverty in this\ncity.\nIn view of this fact, and a positive\nfact it is (If anyone doubt it let him\nask the City Physician), why not con\nstitute the Salvation Army \"The Offi\ncial Charity Agency of Roswell.\"\nThe officers would give their serv\nices for love of humanity; and all the\npublic would have to do would be to\nfind the finances. By this method\nthe salary of a secretary would oe\nsaved. And again, surely no one of\nreason will doubt the most successful\nagent for the betterment of the con\nditions of the poor is the Army.\nTherefore the most intelligent way\nof solving the poverty question in\nRoswell is not the inauguration of\nanother agency, but the official rec-\nognition Of a tried and true charity\norganization already in existence, to\nwit: The Salvation Army. Yours for\nthe betterment of the conditions of\nthe poor.\nSOCIOLOGIST\nSHADE TREES.\nAll kinds first class planted and\nguaranteed to grow. We also carry a\nfull line of fruit trees. Office 2nd and\nMain St., in Seed Store. tf\nTHE SPENCER SEEDLESS\nAPPLE CO.\nBUSINESS CONDITIONS GOOD\nAND PROSPECTS BETTER\nSaid J. A. Graham, secretary of the\nRoswell Commercial Club to a Rec\nord reporter yesterday: \"Business is\nbetter in Roswell right now than it\nwas a year ago, and it is as good as\nit was two years ago this month. In\nfact the effect of .the money strin\ngency has almost entirely worn off\nand the reaction of better times has\nset in. Of course it is always dull\nanywhere this time of the year, and\nwe have to consider that point; Itiit\nconditions are righting themselves\nmuch faster than I anticipated.\n\"In the month of December I re\nceived and answered more letters of\ninquiry about Roswell and the Pecos\nValley than I ever did in any one\nmonth in the history of the club\nThat is certainly a good indication\nfor the future. Most of them came\nfrom men of means with from three\nto ten or fifteen thousand dollars to\ninvest. Most of them expect to come\non prospecting trip to Roswell next\nspring. I look for good times soon.\"\nGood apples at only 5c per pound\nat the Cash Grocery. tf\nTo My Friends.\nI have taken charge of the Cash\nGrocery Store and would be pleased\nto see and meet my friends and ac\nquaintances at this place. I assure\nyou that I will endeavor to please in\nevery particular. Yours for business.\n70tf J. L. GIBBANY,\nManager of the Cash Grocery.\nRussell does carriage work. lOtf\nCard of Thanks.\nWe, the committee appointed by\nVal Verde Camp to solicit funds to\nsend an old Confederate to his native\nstate to enter a Confederate home,\ndesire to return thanks to the Sons\nand Daughters and all friendly to the\ncause for their generous contribution,\nbut particularly the Daughters.\nW. M. FERGUSON,\nJ. E. RUCKER, Com.\nCruse is back at Blacksmithing,\nand needs the money. Go see him. tf.\nHave your buggy fixed by Cruse, tt\n'hone R. B. Jones ror livery rigs.58tf.\nSee J- L. Gibbany at the Cash Gro\ncery for your groceries. 70tf\nCotton seed cake and meal at the\nRoswell Wool Hide Co., phone 30.\nEat good home cooking without the\nlabor of preparing it Sunday. All\nsorts of good things prepared b5' the\nladies of the First M. E. church, on\nsale at the Western Grocery all day\nSaturday, Jan. 18. 70t3\nMRS. RITTER ANNOUNCES\nPROGRAM FOR LYCEUM\nMrs. Stella Ritter, who has charge\nof the musical program, of the next\nschool lyceum number, Monday night,\nhas announced her program, as fol\nlows: Program.\nSextette, \"Down in the Dewy Dell,\"\n(Smart), Mesdames Kilgour, Mc\nClane, Bohannon, Prager, Gibbany,\nMiss Mason.\nBaritone Solo. \"My Desert Queen,\n(Hartwell Jones), Mr. Rogers.\nQuartette, \"Annie Laurie,\" Harmoniz\ned (Buck), Mesdames Ritter, Kil\ngour, Bohannon, Miss Mason.\nContralto Solo, \"If I Were a Rose,\"\n(Hesselburg), Mrs. Sidney Prager.\nQuartette, \"Italia Beloved,\" (Donizet\nti). Mrs. Ritter accompanist.\no\nThe program for the next school\nlecture is the 'best that will have\nbeen rendered before the public in\nthe series.\no\nKilled Monster Bob Cat.\nDr. C. F. Beeson brought in the\nhead and hide of a lar;V bah cat this\nmorning that he killed at his ranch\nten miles up the Hondo. The animal\nweighed thirty pounds and its body\nand head were four feet in length.\nThis is the third big cat Dr. Beeson\nhas killed this season and the sev\nenth one that has been killed in the\nvicinity of his home since last sum\nmer. Every one who sees the hide\nmarvels at its size. It is the largest\nbob cat they have, seen in years.\no\nNotice to Our Customers.\nOn account of needed repairs to\nour oven we may not be around for\na day or two. A. .E. Olson, Home\nBakery. 70t2\no\nGARRETT ON COMMIT\nTEE ON RESOLUTIONS\nHelena, Mont., Jan. 15. Among the\nmembers of the committee on resolu\ntions at the National Wool Growers'\nconvention, are Col. A. J. Ortez of\nNew Mexico, and A. D. Garrett, of\nRoswell, N. M.\nMrs. Charles A. Norvell and Mrs.\nGeorge B. Jewett 'have issued \"at\nhome\" cards for Thursday afternoon,\nJanuary 23, at the home of the for\nmer at 410 Kentucky avenue.\nADVANCEMENT AND PROSPER\nITY OF NEW MEXICO.\n(The following article, signed by Gov\nernor Curry, was published In the\nJanuary issue of \"The Earth,\" the\nSanta Fe Railroad's immigration\nmagazine.)\nTo summarize the growth of New\nMexico during the past yea it is on\nly necessary to turn to the records\nof the four United States land offices\nin this territory, and take therefrom\nthe number of homestead entries\nmade during the past few months.\nDuring the period of seventeen\nmonths, from the beginning of the\nfiscal year, July 1st, 1906, to Decem\nber 1st, 1907, at total of 23,223 land\nentries have been made in New Mex\nico. In the Santa Fe land office, cov\nering central and northwest New\nMexico, 3,291 entries were made; in\nthe Roswell land office, covering the\nsoutheastern couaities, 5,254; in the\nLas Cruces land office, covering the\nsouthwestern portion of the territory,\n1,295; and in the Clayton land office,\ncovering northeast and east New Mex\nico, 13,383.\nThis record of immigration, taken\nfrom the reports of the land offices.\ntakes no account of the thousands of\npeople who have come to New Mexi\nco during this period to find homes\nin the irrigated districts, where they\nhave acquired lands by purchase, or\nwithin the limats of land grants, many\nof which are now 'being subdivided\nand sold in small lots to farmers; nor\ndoes it take aocount of the thousands\nwho have come here to find employ\nment in the cities and towns, in the\nmines and factories, in stock raising\nand other pursuits. The most conserv\native estimates indicate an increase\nin our population, during this brief\nperiod, of not less than 100,000. It is\na record of which New Mexico has\nsome cause to be proud, and which\ngoes far to strengthen the claim the\npeople of New Mexico are now mak\ning before congress, for admission to\nthe Union.\nThe most careful estimates made\nfrom our elaborate school census:\nfrom land office records, from local\nelection returns, and from post office\nrecords, show faat New Mexico, to\nday, has a population of more than\n400,000, as against 195,000 shown bv\nthe census of 1900.\nThe vast majority of this splendid\npopulation increase is of the highest\ntype of American citizenship; men\nwao may be safely trusted with the\nwork of 'building a state, for it is\ndrawn largely from the farming com\nmunities of Iowa and Illinois, of Mis\nsouri and Kansas and Texas, and\nfrom the great agricultural districts\nof the South; men who have found\nout the possibilities of the soil of\nNew Mexico.\nAlmost invariably the farmer who\ncomes to New Mexico stays here, and\nwit.j almost equal certainty, he is fol\nlowed by a little colony of his friends\nand neighbors. This immigration has\nbeen well distributed throughout the\nTerritory, although a very large por\ntion nas found its way into the north\nern and eastern counties, where it has\nbeen demonstrated that good crons\nmay be grown without irrigation. On\nly a few years ago all that e-reat re-\nlion, between the Colorado border on\nthe north, and the plains crossed by\nw.iat is known as the Santa Fe cut\noff, was an unbroken range for cattle\nand sheep. Now it is dotted in all di\nrections with comfortable homes and\nat every cross roads new towns are\nspringing up. There is a single valley\nin central New Mexico, which three\nyears ago was open range for sheep,\nin which today more than 4,000 acres\nof wheat are planted, there being no\nsingle tract of more than 100 acres.\nWe have one county which on its cre\nation, three years ago, had a popula\ntion of 800. Now it has a population\nof not less than 8,000. In the Pecos\nValley, where there are two complet\ned national irrigation projects, and\nn the Mesilla valley, where the great\nElephant Butte storage reservoir is\nsoon to be built, development has\nbeen marvelously rapid. So, also, in\nthe valleys of San Juan county, and\nthroughout the valley of the Rio\nGrande. There is scarcely a county\nin New Mexico today in which some\nlarge private irrigation project is not\nbuilding.\nThe year has been one of great\nprosperity for New Mexico. It has\nbeen marked, not alone by the coming\nof the army of farmers, .out by ;he\nopening of new mines, lead and zinc.\ngold and silver, and coal; by the\nbuilding of new towns and rapid\ngrowth of established ones; by exten\nsion of railroad lines; by a broad, on\nward movement which has marked a\ngreater development, in a fngle year.\nthan during any previous five year pe\nriod in our history.\nNew Mexico is the land of the\nsmall farm. It is coming to be under\nstood that a better and surer liveli\nhood is to be made from ten acres of\nhighly cultivated irrigated land, than\nfrom 160 acres of prairie land in the\nfarming districts of the middle west,\nwhere the farmer is subjected to the\nvagaries of drouth and flood. The Am\nerican farmer has found out some\nthing of this and he is coming to\nNew Mexico in tens and hundreds\nand thousands. He is bringing with\nhim :his energy and pusl and hustle,\nand he is joining in the demand, now\nbeing voiced by every New Mexican,\nthat the people of this territory be\nadmitted to the full rights of citizen\nship. New Mexico has forty million acres\nof public land open to entry. In this\ntremendous area are 'homes for mill\nions, range for vast flocks and herds,\nhighly mineralized districts the sur\nfaces of which have just been scratch\ned; vast forests and unlimited wealth\nof coal. The industrial development\nof this Territory Jias Just begun, but\nit has advanced sufficiently now to\nentitle us to admission to the union.\nThe fact that the Territory has been\nable to advance so far, beneath the\nhandicap of the territorial form of\ngovernment, is in itself positive proof\npositive of the richness of our natural\nresources.\nNEW SUITS FILED\nIN DISTRICT COURT.\nHugh F. Williamson against Birdie\nWilliamson, asking for divorce on the\nground of abandonment. J. T. Evans\nis attorney for plaintiff.\nAlbert Amonett against James A.\nManning, asking judgment for $5,000\ndamages, alleging that defendant on\nDecember 22 last, maliciously had a\nsearch warrant issued against plain\ntiff and searched his premises for\n$90 Cash and two bottles of whisky,\nclaiming said property to have ibeen\nstolen from his place of business, but\ndoing so to injure plaintiff. A. J. Nis\nbet is attorney for plaintiff.\nHoward C. Booth against Sallie\nRichardson Booth, seeking divorce on\nthe ground of abandonment. Reid\nHervey are plaintiff's attorneys.\nDora Arthur against J. H. Arthur,\nasking for divorce on the ground of\ncruelty and non-support; also asking\nfor the custody of four children whose\nages \"range from two to 17 years and\nfor support for said children out of\nproperty of defendant; also seeking\nan injunction to prevent the sale of\nsaid property. A. J. Nisbet is plaint\niff's attorney.\nRoswell Hardware Co. against Mel\nrose Hardware Co., for $214.22, alleg\ned balance due on account. R. E.\nLund is plaintiff's attorney.\nNow is your chance to get two tearrs\nand harness, 4 wagons, block and tack\nle and house moving trucks all for\n$1.00. See R. L. Ballard at Ingersolls.\nCORTELYOU DENIES RE\nPORT OF RESIGNATION.\nWashington, Jan. 15. Secretary\nCortelyou was at his desk today. He\nsaid that there was positively nothing\nin the report of his resignation.\nSecretary Cortelyou's appearance\nat the department is the first since\nhis recent illness about four weeks\nago. He still shows evidence of a se\nvere attack of grip, but expressed the\nhope that he can from now on attend\nto his duties without further trouble.\nHe said the story that he had resign\ned or would resign was absolutely\nwithout foundation. He declared that\nhe had no serious difficulties with\nthe President or any member of the\ncabinet, and that he expected to con\ntinue to serve as Secretary of the\nTreasury. He denied being offered\nthe presidency of the Knickerbocker\nTrust Company, or that he had con\nferred with J. P. Morgan regarding\nit. He had not seen Morgan on his\nrecent trip to New York, he said.\nA SENATOR BROWN SORT\nOF CASE IN CHICAGO.\nChicago, Jan. 15. The case of Mrs.\nThomas Metcalf, who last evening\nshot at Banker John R. Walsh's at\ntorney, Samuel R. Hamill, in the Fed\neral building, parallels In some res\npects the case of Mrs. Annie M. Brad\nley, of Salt Lake, who recently was\nacquitted at Washington after killing\nformer Senator Arthur Brown. Mrs.\nMetcalf has at different times con\nsulted lawyers here with a view of\nbringing legal action against Hamill\nfor alleged whongs she has received\nat his hands. As in the case of Sena\ntor Brown, Mrs. Metcalf is said to\nhave foltowed Hamill across the con\ntinent. Mrs. Metcalf, through her attorney,\nwaived examination when arraigned\nbefore U. S. Commissioner Foote, and\nwas held over to the grand jury on\na bond of $10,000. She stated after\narraignment that her correct name\nwas Mrs. Beatrice Thomas, and ask\ned that further proceedings against\nher Ibe conducted in that name.\nFOR RIDING, DRIVING or HUNT\nING trips, see R. B. Jones, or \"phona\n182. 39t52\nNEW WITNESSES INTRO\nDUCED IN THAW CASE.\nNew York, Jan. 15. Many witness\nes entirely new to the case testified\nat the trial of Harry K. Thaw today,\nand told stories of his eccentricity\nduring the years immediately prior\nto the killing of Stanford White. All\ndeclared that he impressed them as\nbeing irrational. The most interest\ning testimony was that of Christo\npher Biggin, steward of the New\nYork Whist Club, who told of Thaw's\ndoings the day of the tragedy, and\nwho under cross-examination by Je\nrome gave amusing details of a whist\ngame in which Thaw and several men\nof prominence participated.\nCorrect legal blanks. Record Office.\nU. S. WEATHER BUREAU.\n(Local Report. Observation Taken m\n6:00 a. m.)\nRoswell. N. M., Jan, 15. Tempera\nture. Max. (yesterday) 66; min. 27;\nmean, 46.\nPrecipitation, 00; wind W., velocity\n16 miles; weather clear.\nForecast, Roswell and Vicinity:\nTonight, snow and colder; Thurs\nday, fair and colder.\nForecast for New Mexico:\nTonight, snow except in southwest\nportion, colder; Thursday, fair; colder\nin south portion.\nM. WRIGHT.\n1 OflVdAl la Cbarf.","height":"26656","width":"20456"}}
